# A Dwyer pattern's scope: where the requirement is even checked. A scope that
# never opens leaves the requirement passing over nothing -- identical to a
# satisfied one, and the coverage gap a run trace exists to close. referee
# derives the active intervals from the boundary conditions and marks an empty
# scope vacuous.

type K : enum { IDLE, RUN, STOP, ERROR };
data k : K;
data v : integer;

# Whole trace: active across every state, never scope-vacuous.
@glob
globally, it is always the case that v >= 0 holds;

# Opens where the condition first holds. RUN is at state 1, so [1, 4).
@after_run
after k.RUN, it is always the case that v > 0 holds;

# ERROR never occurs in the trace, so the scope never opens: the requirement
# passes without ever being checked, which is exactly what vacuous must catch.
# The body is trivially true, so this passes -- vacuously.
@never_opens
after k.ERROR, it is always the case that v >= -1 holds;

# `between` needs both bounds; the complete RUN..STOP window is [1, 2).
@btw
between k.RUN and k.STOP, it is always the case that v > 0 holds;
